  <span id="freeText15853697722940953364" style="display:none">Auditory hallucination is an inherently interesting topic, so this book was an easy read. However, I wished the author could have organized his flow of ideas better. It was sort of a mish-mash of psychology, history and philosophy, which wasn't tied together very well.<br /><br />And his conclusion/thesis was very lame. He basically ending the book saying (to paraphrase), "A handful of hallucinatory people throughout history have been worth listening to, so you should always pay attention to people who appear crazy."<br /><br />But again, the content of the book was still very interesting, and it's definitely worth reading.</span>
